{"SHOVE":[{"def":"To drive along by the direct and continuous application of strength; to push; especially, to push (a body) so as to make it move along the surface of another body; as, to shove a boat on the water; to shove a table across the floor.","pos":""},{"def":"To push along, aside, or away, in a careless or rude manner; to jostle.","pos":""}],"SHOVEL":[{"def":"An implement consisting of a broad scoop, or more or less hollow blade, with a handle, used for lifting and throwing earth, coal, grain, or other loose substances.","pos":""}],"SHOVEL-NOSED":[{"def":"Having a broad, flat nose; as, the shovel-nosed duck, or shoveler.","pos":""}],"SHOVELBOARD":[{"def":"A board on which a game is played, by pushing or driving pieces of metal or money to reach certain marks; also, the game itself.","pos":""},{"def":"A game played on board ship in which the aim is to shove or drive with a cue wooden disks into divisions chalked on the deck; -- called also shuffleboard.","pos":""}],"SHOVELER":[{"def":"A river duck (Spatula clypeata), native of Europe and America.","pos":""}],"SHOVELFUL":[{"def":"As much as a shovel will hold; enough to fill a shovel.","pos":""}],"SHOVELHEAD":[{"def":"A shark (Sphryna tiburio) allied to the hammerhead, and native of the warmer parts of the Atlantic and Pacific oceans; -- called also bonnet shark.","pos":""}]}